50|$|These {{properties}} {{apply to}} all <b>regular</b> <b>polygons,</b> whether convex or star.|$|R
25|$|Constructible polygon: which <b>regular</b> <b>polygons</b> are {{constructible}} partially {{depends on}} Fermat primes.|$|R
25|$|Finite regular skew polyhedra {{exist in}} 4-space. These finite regular skew polyhedra in 4-space {{can be seen}} as a subset of the faces of uniform 4-polytopes. They have planar <b>regular</b> <b>polygon</b> faces, but regular skew polygon vertex figures.|$|E
25|$|Polygons {{have been}} known since ancient times. The regular polygons were known to the ancient Greeks, with the pentagram, a non-convex <b>regular</b> <b>polygon</b> (star polygon), {{appearing}} {{as early as the}} 7th century B.C. on a krater by Aristonothos, found at Caere and now in the Capitoline Museum.|$|E
25|$|A cyclic polygon is any convex polygon {{about which}} a circle can be circumscribed, passing through each vertex. A well-studied {{example is the}} cyclic quadrilateral. Every <b>regular</b> <b>polygon</b> and every {{triangle}} is a cyclic polygon. A polygon that is both cyclic and tangential is called a bicentric polygon.|$|E
